---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { slate } from '../../data/slate.js';

// Case number, prev/next, and counts derive from slate order — see src/data/slate.js.
const idx = slate.findIndex((c) => c.slug === 'autoco');
const self = slate[idx];
const num = String(idx + 1).padStart(2, '0');
const prev = slate[(idx + slate.length - 1) % slate.length];
const next = slate[(idx + 1) % slate.length];
---
<!--
  ============================================================================
  Remaining (deferred per your call):
  - Image frames (3) — drop in screenshots when ready.
  Resolved: client = a global automaker (anonymized) · Role = Director of UX · Timeframe 2017–2022 ·
            reflection + third "Chose not to" written from your notes.
  Optional: anonymize "Rally" → "the design vendor" if you'd rather not name a partner.
  ============================================================================
-->
<Base title="A global automaker — usability testing at scale · uxward" bodyClass="case">

  <style>
    /* — Frames that hold a real image fill the 16:9 plate edge to edge. — */
    body.case .artifact .frame:has(img) { padding: 0; overflow: hidden; }
    body.case .artifact .frame img { display: block; width: 100%; height: 100%; object-fit: contain; cursor: zoom-in; }

    /* Lightbox — click any artifact image to expand. Mirrors the porte/speakeazy pattern. */
    .lightbox {
      position: fixed;
      inset: 0;
      z-index: 1000;
      background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.33);
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      opacity: 0;
      visibility: hidden;
      transition: opacity 0.25s, visibility 0.25s;
    }

    .lightbox.open { opacity: 1; visibility: visible; }

    .lightbox img { max-width: 92vw; max-height: 88vh; object-fit: contain; }

    .lb-close {
      position: absolute;
      top: var(--space-6);
      right: var(--space-7);
      background: transparent;
      border: 0;
      color: #fff;
      cursor: pointer;
      line-height: 1;
      font-size: 40px;
      opacity: 0.7;
      transition: opacity 0.2s, color 0.2s;
    }

    .lb-close:hover { opacity: 1; color: var(--signature); }
  </style>

  <div class="container breadcrumb">
    <div class="grid">
      <div class="marker">§ ↩</div>
      <div><a href="/work">Back to all work</a></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container title-block">
    <div class="grid">
      <div class="marker">§ 00</div>
      <div>
        <span class="case-num">{num}</span>
        <h1 class="case-title" set:html={self.title} />
        <p class="case-deck">
          Celebrated for their quality and standards, a global automaker realized it was losing to the tech
          industry on both fronts. Across 17 studies and 3,500 hours of testing, I built and led the independent,
          bias-free usability practice that turned guesswork into a closed-loop design process they found 
          so valuable they brought it all in-house.
        </p>
        <div class="artifact hero-preview">
          <div class="frame">
            <img src="/images/autoco/autoco-results.png" alt="Usability-testing program results — the closed-loop research operation that surfaced 300+ issues across 17 studies and 3,500 hours of testing." />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="meta-strip">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ ✻</div>
        <div class="meta-row">
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Client</div>
            <div class="value">Global automaker</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Role</div>
            <div class="value">Director of UX</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Timeframe</div>
            <div class="value">2017 — 2022</div>
          </div>
          <div class="cell">
            <div class="label">Capacity</div>
            <div class="value">Built &amp; led rotating 3–5 person teams</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 01</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">01</span>Context</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">A carmaker that researched <em>everything</em> — and still couldn't see itself.</h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              The company is famous for the volume of its consumer research — market testing, quality
              assurance, constant customer feedback. By any automotive standard, they knew their
              customer cold.
            </p>
            <p>
              But shipping brake pads is not the same as shipping software. The company recognized that its real competition was no
              longer other carmakers; it was the tech industry, where the pace of innovation and the
              quality of the experience set a bar the automotive playbook wasn't built to clear. The
              world-class company was used to shipping software it designed, built, and tested five years prior — and
              that was exactly the problem.
            </p>
            <p>
              The brief: bring independent testing, free of internal confirmation bias, plus design
              and UX alternatives for the experience inside and outside the vehicle. Working across
              three internal divisions and with <a href="https://www.aperioinsights.com/" target="_blank">Aperio Insights</a>, I helped build and run the company's
              first-ever usability tests for its in-car systems.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 02</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">02</span>The problem, named clearly</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">The competition changed industries — and the <em>testing didn't.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              Cars are now judged against phones. A head unit, a voice assistant, a companion app —
              customers measure them against the best software they use every day, not against last
              year's dashboard. Automotive QA was built to catch defects, not to judge an experience
              against the tech industry's bar.
            </p>
            <p>
              And the gap was invisible from the inside. The teams building the systems were the same
              teams evaluating them, so the research kept confirming the company's own assumptions
              instead of surfacing where real users actually struggled.
            </p>
            <blockquote class="cs-pullquote">
              Their competition was no longer other carmakers — it was the tech industry's pace and polish.
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              <strong>The problem: a company famous for research could no longer trust its own
              research to keep pace with tech-industry UX — and needed independent, tech-speed design and testing
              to close the gap before launch, not after.</strong>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 03</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">03</span>The approach</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">Independent eyes, at <em>tech-industry speed.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              The obvious move was to lean harder on the existing research apparatus — more studies,
              same machine. I didn't. Its scale was real, but so was its blind spot: it was structured
              to validate, not to challenge. The only way to get honest answers was to put the testing
              in independent hands.
            </p>
            <p>
              So we stood up a dedicated, outside testing practice. Over the program, that meant more
              than 500 moderated, in-person usability tests and 3,500-plus hours of live-streamed,
              recorded, logged, and reported research — rotating teams of three to five researchers,
              testing ten to twelve hours a day, up to three days a week, across 17 separate studies:
              head units, dashboards, at-speed voice UI, mobile apps, and more.
            </p>
            <p>
              New thinking needed new tools, so we built them — our own logging, study-tracking, and
              rapid-analysis tooling, and even our own way to structure simulated driving. We were, by
              the company's own account, the first team to run usability studies on their software. And the
              point was never to run tests; it was to wire results straight back to the design teams
              fast enough to iterate inside the same engagement. A closed loop, not a report.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="choices">
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">Chose to</div>
              <div class="val"><strong>Test independently of the people who built the systems.</strong> The only way past confirmation bias was to take evaluation out of the builders' hands.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">Chose to</div>
              <div class="val"><strong>Test in real context</strong> — real vehicles, real conditions, including at speed — instead of clean-room scenarios that flatter the design.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">Chose to</div>
              <div class="val"><strong>Build a closed loop, not a deliverable.</strong> Results fed back to design teams fast enough to validate and iterate within the engagement. Turnaround times measured in hours and days, not weeks and months.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">Chose <strong>not</strong> to</div>
              <div class="val">Lean on the client's celebrated research machine. Its strength — scale and documentaion — was also its blind spot, so we built outside it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">Chose <strong>not</strong> to</div>
              <div class="val">Port legacy automotive QA methods onto a tech-paced UX problem. New thinking needed new tools and a new process.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="choice-row">
              <div class="key">Chose <strong>not</strong> to</div>
              <div class="val">Hire senior researchers to de-risk it. I staffed the program with sharp people breaking into UX, gave them their first studies and a marquee logo, and grew them — <strong>all now senior in their own right.</strong></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 04</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">04</span>The work itself</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">A research <em>operation</em>, not a deliverable.</h2>
          <div class="cs-prose" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-9);">
            <p>
              The work here isn't a screen — it's the machine that produced the answers. Three parts
              of it carried the program.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="artifacts">
            <div class="artifact">
              <div class="frame">
                <img src="/images/autoco/autoco-testing-setup.jpg" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="The live-streamed testing rig — a branded steering wheel and an iPad running the test prototype, wired to camera arms on stands and a bank of laptops for the moderator and remote observers." />
              </div>
              <div class="caption-grid">
                <span class="num">01</span>
                <div class="body">
                  <h4>The live-streamed testing rig</h4>
                  <p class="cap">
                    More than 500 moderated tests and 3,500 hours, run in real vehicles and conditions,
                    streamed and logged so stakeholders anywhere could watch the customer struggle in
                    real time.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="artifact">
              <div class="frame">
                <img src="/images/autoco/summary.jpg" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="The closeout dashboard for a single usability study — System Usability Score trending toward the 85 target (average 80), aesthetic rating averaging 4.1 of 5, over 55 testing days, 305 tasks, and 2,071 hours." />
              </div>
              <div class="caption-grid">
                <span class="num">02</span>
                <div class="body">
                  <h4>One study's closeout — one of 17</h4>
                  <p class="cap">
                    The end-of-run scorecard for a single usability study, tracking System Usability
                    (SUS) toward the 85 target and aesthetic ratings over its full duration. Each of
                    the 17 studies in the program closed out with a readout like this one.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="artifact">
              <div class="frame">
                <img src="/images/autoco/loop.png" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Diagram of the closed-loop research process — a continuous cycle of seven steps: study kickoff and expectations, draft study plan, review and revise plan, recruit participants, execute study (with the report drafted live), review and report results, and design-team iteration that loops back to the start. A subordinate branch shows how large studies scaled up to multiple test days and two back-to-back team shifts (7 AM–1 PM, then 1 PM–7 PM)." />
              </div>
              <div class="caption-grid">
                <span class="num">03</span>
                <div class="body">
                  <h4>The closed-loop process</h4>
                  <p class="cap">
                    17 studies wired into one cadence that fed results back fast enough to iterate
                    inside the engagement — the thing that turned testing from an audit into a design
                    engine.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="cs-prose" style="margin-top: var(--space-9);">
            <p>
              The program caused major ripples across the company globally. Everyone wanted to see how the
              North American team was designing, testing, and building the new HMI so quickly and with such high quality.
              The company's chairman himself stopped by to watch a session, and teams from around the world
              asked to adopt the practice. Once the model proved out, the same approach went on to test 
              power wheelchairs, at-speed voice UI, mobile apps, head units, and dashboards.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs outcomes-bleed">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.78);">§ 05</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">05</span>Outcomes</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">
            Stakeholders stopped guessing the customer's mind — and the company brought usability testing in-house for good.
          </h2>
          <div class="outcomes-stats">
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="label">Research run</div>
              <div class="figure">3.5K hrs</div>
              <div class="desc">500+ moderated, in-person tests in real conditions.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="label">Breadth</div>
              <div class="figure">17</div>
              <div class="desc">Separate studies across head units, voice, apps, and more.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <div class="label">Issues surfaced &amp; fixed</div>
              <div class="figure">300+</div>
              <div class="desc">Each paired with a recommendation, across multiple platforms.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="marker">§ 06</div>
        <div>
          <div class="cs-eyebrow"><span class="num">06</span>Reflection</div>
          <h2 class="cs-head">What I'd reverse. What I <em>carried forward.</em></h2>
          <div class="cs-prose">
            <p>
              <strong>The decision I'd reverse:</strong> I built our relationship with the automaker and let
              the relationship with <a href="https://rallyinteractive.com/" target="_blank">Rally</a>
               — the design vendor whose work we were testing — fend for
              itself. With the automaker sitting between us as the middleman, the structure quietly pitted two
              vendors against each other. We were there to validate and elevate Rally's work; too often
              it must have felt like we were there to break it. I should have fought for a direct,
              close partnership with Rally from day one — because research is only as useful as the
              design team's willingness to act on it, and I left that to chance.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>The surprise:</strong> how readily drivers pull their attention off the road. It
              reads as obvious, but it was visceral in testing — people lifting their hands off the
              simulated wheel to lean in and squint at a font, or getting lost three menus deep just to
              do something simple. A big touchscreen that makes you look away to operate it is a
              genuinely bad idea. Simple, high-level, glanceable interaction you can use without looking
              went from "nice" to mission-critical.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>What I carried forward:</strong> never be afraid to step into the dark and build
              the thing that doesn't exist yet. We had to invent most of our apparatus — the logging,
              the study-tracking, the rapid analysis, even how to structure simulated driving — to run
              studies no one at the company had run before. If the tool you need doesn't exist, you build
              it. It's the same instinct behind <a href="speakeazy"><em>Speakeazy</em></a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="prevnext">
      <div class="pn-cell prev">
        <div class="label">Previous case</div>
        <a href={`/work/${prev.slug}`} set:html={`${prev.title}`} />
      </div>
      <div class="pn-cell next">
        <div class="label">Next case</div>
        <a href={`/work/${next.slug}`} set:html={`${next.title}`} />
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="lightbox" data-lightbox aria-hidden="true">
    <button type="button" class="lb-close" aria-label="Close">×</button>
    <img alt="" />
  </div>

  <script>
    const lb = document.querySelector('.lightbox');
    const lbImg = lb.querySelector('img');

    function openLb(src) {
      lbImg.setAttribute('src', src);
      lb.classList.add('open');
      lb.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'false');
    }
    function closeLb() {
      lb.classList.remove('open');
      lb.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'true');
    }

    lb.querySelector('.lb-close').addEventListener('click', closeLb);
    lb.addEventListener('click', (e) => { if (e.target === lb || e.target === lbImg) closeLb(); });
    document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
      if (lb.classList.contains('open') && e.key === 'Escape') closeLb();
    });

    document.querySelectorAll('.artifact .frame img').forEach((img) => {
      img.addEventListener('click', () => openLb(img.getAttribute('src')));
    });
  </script>
</Base>
